ConsistencyRemarks.remarks:
        It is possible for a transaction to see an inconsistent view of memory. See the following example:
        
using(STMTransaction tx = STMTransaction.Create())
{
  a = var1.Read();
  // another transaction commits changes to var1 and var2 at this point
  b = var2.Read();
  ...
}
        
        In this example, the transaction will see a value of var1 from before the other transaction committed, and a
        value of var2 from after it committed. The values will be inconsistent. When the transaction in the example calls
        , the inconsistency will be detected and the transaction will be aborted, but until
        that point, if the transaction in the example is not written with this possibility in mind, the inconsistency may cause
        it to behave unexpectedly. If your algorithm requires consistency, you can call  or
         any time to validate the consistency of the transaction, or you can use the
         option, but see their documentation for proper usage.
